<DOC><DOCNO> AP900403-0147 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-90 2041EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-WarChildren     04-03 0123</FIRST><SECOND>AM-War Children,110</SECOND><HEAD>Actress Liv Ullmann Testifies on Plight of Children</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto WX17</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Actress Liv Ullmann told a Senate subcommitteeTuesday that every other movement of the second hand signals thedeath of a child from neglect, disease or war.   ``Every day in our world, from neglect, from preventabledisease, from war, 40,000 children die,'' the film and stage startold the Senate Labor and Human Resources subcommittee on children,family, drugs and alcoholism.   Ullmann spoke as a goodwill ambassador for the United NationsChildren's Fund, better known as UNICEF. The subcommittee wasreceiving testimony on the effects of war on children.   Ullmann included in that category ``the terrible wars on thestreets,'' which is how she described homelessness.</TEXT></DOC>